## 7. Title parsing (the messy part)

Titles are inconsistent: `Jamie & Lee 🎹`, `William, Sophia & Lee 🎹` (two students), `OFF TODAY - Miles & JD 🎹`, `Thomas & Erik 🎤`, trailing spaces, typos ("TOADY"), unknown nicknames.

**Two-layer strategy:**
1. **Rules layer (fast, free, deterministic):**
   - Strip status prefixes (`OFF TODAY`, etc.) → set `canceled`/flag.
   - Detect instrument from emoji (🎹→piano, 🎤→vocal). Missing emoji → flag, don't drop.
   - Split on `&`; the **last** name = teacher (match against `teachers`); the rest = student(s), split on commas → **emit one billable event per student** (fixes the multi-student drop).
   - Resolve each student via `student_aliases` (lowercased). No match → `unknown` → review queue.
2. **LLM fallback (Claude, only when rules are unsure):** send the raw title + the known roster and ask for structured JSON `{students[], teacher, instrument, status}` using tool use / a strict schema. Use it only for titles the rules can't confidently parse, to keep cost trivial. (SDK + tool use: https://docs.claude.com/en/api/overview)

Every parse writes its decision + confidence to `audit_log` so you can tune the rules.

---

## 8. Exception / review queue

Anything not confidently billable goes here instead of being silently dropped or wrongly billed:
- unknown student, ambiguous multi-name, missing instrument, missing confirmation, price rule not found.
A human resolves in the dashboard (pick/create student, add an alias, mark canceled). Resolving an `unknown` and adding the alias means the *next* run auto-resolves it. This is the single biggest reliability win over the current silent-skip behavior.

---

## 9. Two business lines, one engine

Use a small **strategy per business line** so the engine stays shared:

```ts
interface BillingStrategy {
  classify(event): Status;
  parse(event): ParsedEvent;
  aggregate(events): Invoice[];   // MLIG groups by student×month; MLIE = 1:1
  docNumber(invoice): string;
}
```
- `MligLessonsStrategy` — aggregate by student × billing-month, multi-line.
- `MlieGigsStrategy` — one invoice per gig, single line (performer fee).

Same ingest, review queue, QBO push, and audit — only classify/parse/aggregate differ.

